The Dog That Did Not Bark: A Defense of Return Predictability (Replication)

Table 1 - Forecasting regressions
\(b\) \(t\) \(R^2(\%)\) \(\sigma(bx)(\%)\)
Regression
\(R_{t+1} = a + b(D_t / P_t ) + \epsilon_{t+1}\) 3.01 2.33 5.7 4.8
\(R_{t+1} - R^f_t = a + b(D_t / P_t ) + \epsilon_{t+1}\) 3.02 2.32 5.7 4.8
\(D_{t+1} / D_t = a + b(D_t / P_t ) + \epsilon_{t+1}\) -1.12 -1.54 2.6 1.8
\(r_{t+1} = a + b(d_t - p_t ) + \epsilon^r_{t+1}\) 0.09 1.93 4.0 3.9
\(\Delta d_{t+1} = a + b(d_t - p_t ) + \epsilon^{dp}_{t+1}\) -0.04 -1.32 1.9 1.6

The result is quite similar to papers result. The coefficients of dividend growth and log dividend growth are negative as expected, as high dividend/price ratio implies low price, which indicates that the dividend in the future would be low.
